@database "cblog.guide"

@Node main "Cyril Brown's Logger"
                          'Cyril Brown's Logger'
                               Version 1.0
                      Program by Wayne A.O. Hogue
              Copyright (c) 1995 by MicroMouse Productions
                          All Rights Reserved

'Cyril Brown's Logger' also referred to as CBLOG is a program to log QSOs
for the CQ World Wide Contest.

Notices:
           @{"      Copyrights      " link copyrights}     @{"       License        " link License}
           @{"        Terms         " link terms}     @{"    Program Backup    " link program_backup}
           @{"      Disclaimer      " link disclaimer}     @{"       Warranty       " link warranty}
           @{"      Trademarks      " link trademarks}     @{" Support and Upgrades " link support}
           @{"   Acknowledgements   " link acknowledgements}

Program: The program has been designed to be very simple to use once you
         start entering QSOs in the contest.  The computer automatically
         performs must of its functions so that you do not have to learn
         a multitude of complicated keystrokes to turn these functions on
         and off.  There is though a certain unavoidable amount of
         complexity in setting up all the features of the program.  These
         features are reached through the use of @{" pull-down menus " link menus}.
         
         CBLOG uses a series of windows to show you information and to
         allow for input of data into the program.  These windows can be
         positioned anywhere on the screen but you can not rearrange the
         data in the windows.  These windows can be opened on either a
         HIRES or HIRES-INTERLACED screen on either NTSC or PAL computers.
         A feature in WorkBench allows for the creation of Public screens.
         A Public screen will allow the windows from any program (designed
         to utilize this feature) to be opened on it.  The screens opened
         by CBLOG are Public screens so you may have other programs that
         will operate on the screens of CBLOG.  Also the windows in CBLOG
         can be made to 'Jump' or move to the 'WorkBench' screen (a Public
         screen) or any other Public screen. To do this select from the
         'Windows' menu the 'Jump Windows' menu item.  The windows will
         close down and after a short time the windows will reopen on
         another Public screen.
         
         The main windows in CBLOG are the @{" Contest Window " link wdw_console} which is the
         main window for input of new QSOs and for accessing the pull-down
         menus.  The @{" Summary Window " link wdw_summary} displays all the data about QSOs,
         points, etc. so that you can see how well you are doing in the
         contest.  The @{" Partials Window " link wdw_partials} shows any CallSigns from QSOs
         that you have already made as you type in characters for a new
         CallSign.  Comparisons or partial matches are made as soon as the
         first character of the new CallSign is typed in.
         The @{" Zone Window " link wdw_zone} displays the zones that you already
         have QSOs for.  The @{" Rate Window " link wdw_rate} shows how many QSOs you are
         making per hour plus for the new CallSign being entered displayed
         is the Country Name, Zone, Continent, Beam Heading, and what type
         of Multiplier the new QSO will be.  The above features occur
         automatically and can not be started or turned off by the user.
         
         Before starting the contest, a disk file should be opened to store
         the QSOs in.  From the 'Project' menu choose the 'Open Log File'
         menu item and then either the 'New' or 'Old' submenu item.  The
         'New' submenu item opens a new disk file and the 'Old' submenu
         item opens an existing disk file.  After choosing either 'New' or
         'Old' an ASL file requester will open so that you can choose
         the path and file name.  The program assumes that only one contest
         is being stored per log file.
         
         All data for the CallSign Prefixes and QSOs is kept in RAM memory
         in the computer for fast access and comparisons.  There is no
         danger of losing all your QSOs because every time you enter a new
         QSO or edit an old QSO it is written immediately to the log disk
         file.  In case of a power failure, you will lose any QSO that is
         somewhere in the process of being entered into the program.
         
         During the contest there are three methods for @{" Backing up " link backup}
         your QSOs.  CBLOG can automatically read or change frequencies on
         some @{" radios " link set_radio}.  Also if you have a @{" packet radio " link packet_general} another window"
         can be opened to show the DXs that are being logged by the packet
         radio station.  If CBLOG can control the radio and packet radio
         at the same time then you can also send DXs to the packet radio
         station.
         
         At any time you can stop entering new QSOs and scroll back and
         forth through the old QSOs.  Any old QSO can be edited and control
         is returned immediately so that a new QSO can be entered.
         
         For the program to match CallSign prefixes and inform you of what
         country, zone, etc. it belongs to it needs a database located in
         a file named 'cblog.pref'.  This database can be @{" edited " link edit1}.

         After the contest a written report has to be sent in to the Contest
         Headquarters.  From the pull-down menus each type of report can
         be printed out individually or as a whole group.  If any of the
         QSOs have been edited to ensure that the report is scored
         correctly select the 'Rescore Log' menu item from the 'Project'
         menu.  After the rescoring a requester will ask if the log should
         be rewritten to the file.  Choose 'Okay' if the scoring has
         changed.
@EndNode


