@Node wdw_open "Get Screen Type"
This window opens on the 'WorkBench' screen whenever the 'cblog.cnfg' file
can not be found.  Select the type of screen you would like the program to
be opened on. The possibilities are 'HiRes', 'HiRes Interlace' and the
'WorkBench' screens.  The screen opened will be either an NTSC or a PAL
screen.

When your screen selection can be read from the 'cblog.cnfg' file, then
the program will open on that type of screen.
@EndNode 




@Node wdw_console "Contest/Console Window"
The 'Contest' or 'Console' window is the main input window for the program.
All new QSOs are logged in this window plus viewing of old QSOs, control
of the radio, changing bands, sending DXs to the packet radio and access
to the pull-down menus.

The current Zulu time and Zulu date are displayed in the top row in this
window.  The Zulu time is calculated by taking the current local time
that your computer is set for and adding or subtracting the hours and
minutes that your @{" time zone is different from Universal Time " link user_data}.

The gadgets displayed in the top row are dependant on whether you are
operating in @{" manual or radio mode " link set_radio}. In 'Manual Mode' the cycle gadget
on the left selects the band that you are currently working.  The next
cycle gadget selects the mode for the band.  The next gadget titled
'Delete' is ghosted (in a disabled state and can not be used) until a new
QSO has been added to your list of successful QSOs.  If for some reason
the latest QSO should not have been added to your list then select this
gadget to delete the QSO from your list and from the log file.  A requester
will ask you if you really want to delete the QSO.  The last gadget, '?'
opens the help file using AmigaGuide.

In 'Radio Mode' the 'Delete' and '?' gadgets have the same function as for
'Manual Mode'.  For the new gadgets the gadget on the left displays the
current frequency that the radio is set for.  This gadget can be used
to change the frequency on the radio.  Place the mouse pointer over the
frequency digit that should be changed and click the left mouse button.
If the pointer was over the lower half of the digit the value of the digit
will increase by one but if it was over the upper half of the digit the
value of the digit will decrease by one.  The next gadget is the cycle
gadget that allows you to set the mode for the band that you are working.
The 'v' gadget moves down one band and the '^' gadget moves up one band.
In 'Radio Mode' when the bands are changed the program remembers the
frequency that the radio was set for.  Thus whenever you return to a band
the radio is set for the frequency last used there.

There are five gadgets (six if you count '?' gadget) in a column on the
right side of the window.  The 'P' gadget is used when you are operating
in 'Radio Mode' and assisted by the packet radio.  The normal condition of
the  'P' gadget is ghosted.  When a new QSO is added to the log file the
'P' gadget is unghosted.  Clicking on the 'P' gadget sends a DX about this
latest QSO to the packet radio.  Pressing the 'F5' function key also will
send the latest QSO to the packet radio.  The other four gadgets are used
with the QSO database in the computer's memory and when there are more than
one screenful of QSOs.

The 'T' gadget displays from the top of the database starting with the
first QSO.  The 'B' gadget displays from the bottom of the database
starting with the last QSO.  The 'v' gadget allows you to scroll down the
database towards the bottom one screenful at a time.  The '^' gadget
allows you to scroll up through the database one screenful at a time. If
you prefer not using the rodent to scroll through the database of QSOs use
the up and down arrow keys instead.  The up and down arrow keys scroll
through the database one QSO at a time unless you simultaneously hold
down the shift key which causes scrolling at a screenful at a time.

Most of the window is used for displaying your old QSOs with the bottom
row being reserved to show the data as you input characters for your newest
QSO.  A new QSO always starts with entering data for the CallSign first.
Starting with the first character entered the program makes partial matches
with old QSOs in the database and shows any of these matches in the
'Partials Window'.  Lower case letters entered for CallSigns are
automatically capitalized.  Besides doing the partial matches the computer
also checks the CallSign Prefix database and as soon as a match is made
the country name, zone, continent and beam heading are shown.  Also if
this QSO will qualify as a Multiplier this is also shown by a symbol
indicating what type of Multiplier it is.  While entering the CallSign
the left and right arrow keys can be used to move one character at a time
through the word.  Pressing the shift key simultaneously with the left or
right arrow key causes the cursor to jump to the beginning or the end of
the CallSign.  The entire CallSign can be deleted by pressing the 'F10'
function key.  The 'backspace' key will delete a character to the left of
the cursor and the 'delete' key will delete the character under the cursor.
The cursor can be anyplace in the CallSign and a new character will be
inserted at that location.

When the CallSign has been entered, press the 'space bar' or the <return>
key.  The Rst, Zone and rSt are automatically entered for you.  If the
CallSign is for the United States the Zone field is not filled in because
the same CallSign Prefix could belong to many zones.  The input cursor is
positioned in the Zone field.  If the zone is wrong either use the
'backspace' key or the 'F10' function key to delete it and then enter the
correct zone.  When all entries are correct, press the <return> key to
add the QSO to your database.  The 'space bar' can be used to move from
field to field.  Once all four fields contain data and with the input
cursor in any of the fields, pressing the <return> key adds the QSO to the
database.  Pressing the 'tab' key causes the cursor to move between the
CallSign and Zone fields while skipping the Rst and rSt fields.  Pressing
the 'Esc' or 'Escape' key clears the data from all four fields.

The function keys provide different uses:

F1:  Toggles between displaying the 'Summary' and 'Partials' windows on a
     HIRES screen.  If the windows have been depth arranged using the
     'Front/Back' gadget it may take two presses on the key to toggle
     the windows.  What is happening is that the window is being made to
     display itself in front of all other windows.  For example, if the
     'Console' window is on top of the 'Summary' and 'Partials' windows
     pressing the key once will display one of the windows in front of the
     'Console' window and pressing the key again will display the other
     window in front.

F2:  Toggles between displaying the 'Rate' and 'Zones' windows on a HIRES
     screen.  If the windows have been depth arranged using the 
     'Front/Back' gadget it may take two presses on the key to toggle
     the windows.  What is happening is that the window is being made to
     display itself in front of all other windows.  For example, if the
     'Console' window is on top of the 'Rate' and 'Zones' windows
     pressing the key once will display one of the windows in front of the
     'Console' window and pressing the key again will display the other
     window in front.

F3:  If any windows are covering the 'Console' window, then press the 'F3'
     key to display the 'Console' window in front of all of the windows.

F4:  If any windows are covering the 'Packet' window, then press the 'F4'
     key to display the 'Packet' window in front of all of the windows.

F5:  When in 'Radio Mode' and using packet radio, pressing the 'F5'
     function key sends a DX about the newest QSO added to the database to
     the packet radio.

F6:  To edit an old QSO move through the database using the up and down
     arrow keys.  When the QSO is highlighted, press the 'F6' function key
     to commence editing the old QSO.  The old data about the QSO will be
     displayed so that you can edit it.  Instead of pressing the 'F6'
     function key just position the mouse pointer over the QSO (it does not
     have to be highlighted) and press the left mouse button.  Edit mode is
     entered.  If this was the wrong QSO just press the mouse button again
     (do not move the pointer) to abort edit mode.

F7:  Repeated pressing of the 'F7' function key will show a list of all
     the countries contacted for the current band in the 'Summary Window'.
     If you do not recognize the ID Prefix for the country, place the mouse
     pointer over it and press the left button.  Country name, continent
     and beam heading will be shown in the 'Rate Window' but the zone will
     not be shown.

F8:  Enter a zone number in the CallSign field and press the 'F8' function
     key.  CallSign Prefixes that belong to that zone will be shown in the
     'Partials Window'.  If there is more than one screenful of Prefixes,
     repeated pressing of the 'F8' function key will move through the
     entire list.  If you do not recognize the CallSign Prefix, place
     the mouse pointer over it and press the left button.  Country name,
     continent, beam heading, zone and type of Multiplier will be shown in
     the 'Rate Window'.

F9:  Toggles between displaying 'GoTo CallSign' and 'GoTo Number' and
     provides a field to enter the CallSign or number.  After the number
     is entered and the <return> key is pressed, the QSO for that number
     will be displayed.  If a CallSign is entered and it can be found in
     the database the first one will be shown.  Press the <return> key
     again and if there is a next one in the database it will be shown.
     As long as another key is not pressed you can move through the data-
     base finding each occurrence of the CallSign.

F10: Clears all characters from the field that the cursor is currently
     positioned in.
@EndNode




@Node wdw_summary "Summary Window"
The 'Summary Window' displays your results in the CQWW Contest.  User
changeable colors are used to highlight the Title, the Totals and the
Band currently being worked.

You can change the Band you are working by placing the mouse pointer on
the line for the new Band and clicking once with the left mouse button.

When the windows are displayed on a 'HiRes' screen, the 'Summary Window'
and the 'Partials Window' are displayed on top of one another.  Use the
'F1' function key to toggle between displaying either the 'Partials Window'
or the 'Summary Window'.  If you have used the 'Depth' gadget to change the
order of the windows or one of the other program functions has changed the
order, you may have to press the 'F1' key twice to bring the window to the
front for display.
@EndNode




@Node wdw_partials "Partials Window"
The 'Partials Window' displays old CallSigns as you enter a new CallSign
in the 'Contest Window'.  This operation occurs automatically and can not
be turned off.

Starting with the first letter or number entered for the new CallSign a
comparison is made with the CallSigns from your previous QSOs for the band
you are currently working.  If a match is made, the old CallSign is
displayed.  Two types of matches are made.  One type matches characters
starting from the left side of the old CallSign whereas the other type
matches characters from the right side of the CallSign.  For example, if
VE had been entered for the new CallSign, a partial match from the left
could show VE5TL and a partial match from the right could show CE5VE.

The old, matched CallSigns are displayed in four columns.  The two columns
on the left display matches from the left side of the CallSign.  The two
columns on the right display matches from the right side.  A different
color is used for the right side matches.  This color is user adjustable.

When the windows are displayed on a 'HiRes' screen, the 'Partials Window'
and the 'Summary Window' are displayed on top of one another.  Use the
'F1' function key to toggle between displaying either the 'Partials Window'
or the 'Summary Window'.  If you have used the 'Depth' gadget to change the
order of the windows or one of the other program functions has changed the
order, you may have to press the 'F1' key twice to bring the window to the
front for display.
@EndNode




@Node wdw_zone "Zones Window"
The 'Zones Window' displays numbers from 1 to 40 for the allowable CQ
zones.  As you change from one band to another, the CQ zones automatically
display the zones for the currently selected band.  The zones that are
matched with each QSO are shown in a user selectable color.

When the windows are displayed on a 'HiRes' screen, the 'Zone Window' and
the 'Rate Window' are displayed on top of one another.  Use the 'F2'
function key to toggle between displaying either the 'Zone Window' or the
'Rate Window'.  If you have used the 'Depth' gadget to change the order of
the windows or one of the other program functions has changed the order,
you may have to press the 'F2' key twice to bring the window to the front
for display.

Special Feature:
     Recall that the zones displayed are for the band that is currently
     being worked.  Place the mouse pointer over any one of the zone
     numbers and press the left mouse button.  The 'Partials Window' will
     be brought to the front and the CallSign Prefixes associated with that
     zone will be displayed.  The Prefixes shown in color (not the default
     color which is usually black) are from the countries that you do not
     yet have a QSO for.  If you do not recognize a Prefix then place the
     mouse pointer over it and press the left mouse button.  The
     'Rate Window' will be brought to the front and the country name,
     beam heading, continent and zone will be displayed.
@EndNode




@Node wdw_rate "Rate Window"
The 'Rate Window' displays the number of QSOs that you are making per hour.
Two rates are shown.  One is calculated using the ten most recent QSOs and
the other is calculated using the last one hundred QSOs.

As you enter a new CallSign and as soon as a match can be made with a
prefix for a country, then that country's name is displayed in the window
along with the Beam Heading to that country.  Also automatically shown is
the continent that the country is in plus its CQ zone.  For countries that
cover more than one CQ zone only one CQ zone can be shown.  Also if this
new CallSign will give you a Multiplier then the symbol for the type of
Multiplier will be shown.

When the windows are displayed on a 'HiRes' screen, the 'Zone Window' and
the 'Rate Window' are displayed on top of one another.  Use the 'F2'
function key to toggle between displaying either the 'Zone Window' or the
'Rate Window'.  If you have used the 'Depth' gadget to change the order of
the windows or one of the other program functions has changed the order,
you may have to press the 'F2' key twice to bring the window to the front
for display.
@EndNode




@Node user_data "Setting User Data"
The information entered in the 'User Data Window' determines how the
program will make determinations for the contest.  Your CallSign is the
main value from which all other values in the program are derived.  Enter
your CallSign and press the <return> key.  If your CallSign is found in the
data base, the name of your country will now be displayed.

Now click on the 'Set' gadget and the program will look up the default
values for your CallSign and country.  The ITU zone is not currently used
but the CQ zone is used for scoring the CQWW contest.  Some countries have
multiple CQ zones so the number of the zone displayed may be incorrect for
you.  If so, please enter the correct zone.

The longitude and latitude defaults are usually based on the center of the
country.  Enter the longitude and latitude for your location and the beam
headings calculated will then be more accurate.

Contests are based on Zulu time but you can leave the time clock in your
computer set to your local time.  Enter the number of hours that your time
varies from Zulu time.  The number entered is a floating point number that
can be either positive or negative.  For example, if your time is six hours
and thirty minutes ahead of Zulu time enter 6.5 in the gadget.

The date format used for display and printing can be set to either of three
formats.  The formats are 'Month-Day-Year', 'Day-Month-Year' and
'Year-Month-Day'.

The 'Reset' gadget returns all user information to the values that existed
before this window was opened.
@EndNode




@Node edit1 "Editing Countries and Prefixes"
The CallSign Prefix list supplied with CBLOG is a fully user editable data-
base. The database was compiled from a file titled 'DXCC.LIST' that was
supplied by Pete Hardie, VE5VA.  This file was a modified version of a file
that was derived from the ARRL countries list and sent out on usenet by
wmb@ulysses.att.com (W M Brelsford).

The main window displays names and identifying (ID) prefixes for countries
in two sets of columns in different colors.  The database design defines
the country first and then attaches the CallSign prefixes to the country
definition.

  . To examine/edit a country, place the mouse pointer over a name or
    ID prefix and click the left mouse button once.

  . To move forwards and backwards through the database click on either the
    'Forward' or 'Backward' gadgets.

  . Click on the 'Add' gadget and a new country can be added to the end
    of the database.

  . Click on the 'Delete' gadget and the mouse button changes to a pair of
    scissors.  Place the mouse pointer over the country to be deleted and
    press the left mouse button.  A requester now appears to confirm that
    you really want to delete this country and all the CallSign Prefixes
    attached to it.

  . Click on the 'Sort' gadget and the countries are sorted according to
    the ID Prefix for the country.  Also the CallSign Prefixes are
    sorted.

  . Click on the 'Search' gadget and you can find a country either by
    making comparisons based on the Name or the ID Prefix.

  . The 'Help' gadget activates the AmigaGuide help utility.

  . Click on the 'Okay' gadget to end the current session of Editing
    Countries and Prefixes and return to the main part of the program.
    
Note: As new countries and prefixes are created or old ones are changed
      these changes are not being written to disk but are only contained
      in RAM memory in the computer.  In case of a power failure, these
      changes should be written to a disk file as soon as possible.
@EndNode




@Node edit2 "Search for Country"
A country can be searched for either by ID Prefix or by Name.  Click on the
radio button for your choice and then type in either the Name or the ID
Prefix.  It does not matter whether you use capitals or small letters.

After typing in your selection press the <return> key or click on the
'Okay' gadget.  If a match is found for your request, the match will be
displayed in a different color.
@EndNode




@Node edit3 "Editing Countries"
Countries are defined by their Name, ID Prefix and Division.  When CBLOG
stores QSOs it uses the ID Prefix and Division to reference the country.

ID Prefix
---------
The ID Prefix must be a UNIQUE combination of letters and numbers.  The
ID Prefixes in the supplied database are the primary amateur prefixes for
the countries but you can use any other unique set of characters.  The
space character is an illegal character for the ID Prefix and CBLOG will
remove the spaces.

Divisions
---------
What are divisions?  Larger countries, such as Canada, are divided into
more than one CQ zone.  You can sub-divide the country into as many
divisions as there are zones and then use a unique name for each division.
For Canada, the country is divided by provinces.  The user has no control
over the number assigned to each division.  Countries with divisions are
created by using the ID Prefix for an old country when adding a new country
to the database.

Country Name
------------
The name can be any name that you choose.  Leading spaces before the name
will be removed.

Continents
----------
Use the cycle gadget to select the continent that the country is on.
Points are determined according to country and continent.

Hours from UTC
--------------
Set the number of hours that the country's time differs from Universal
Time.  If the country is 7 hours and 15 minutes ahead of Universal Time
then enter 7.25 in the gadget.

Latitude and Longitude
----------------------
Enter the latitude and longitude for the center of the country (or another
point in the country) and CBLOG will calculate Beam Headings from your
location to the country.

Latitude is a measurement of distance from the equator to some point.
Latitudes North of the equator are entered as positive latitudes and those
South of the equator are entered as negative latitudes. The equator is at
0 degrees, the North Pole is at +90 degrees and the South Pole is at -90
degrees.

An imaginary line extending from pole to pole and passing through
Greenwich, United Kingdom, is know as the Prime Meridian.  A longitude is
a measurement of distance from the Prime Meridian to some point.
Longitudes West of the Prime Meridian are entered as positive longitudes
and those East of the Prime Meridian are entered as negative longitudes. 

Display Columns
---------------
Two sets of columns are displayed in different colors.  Each set of columns
displays the CallSign Prefixes (including prefix, suffix, ITU and CQ zones)
associated with the country.  To edit a CallSign Prefix, place the mouse
pointer over the CallSign Prefix, Suffix or Zone and click the left mouse
button once.

Gadgets
-------
  . 'Forward' and 'Backward' gadgets allow you to move forward and backward
    in the database of CallSign Prefixes.

  . 'Add' gadget allows a new CallSign Prefix to be added to the end of
    the Prefix database.

  . Click on the 'Delete' gadget and the mouse button changes to a pair of
    scissors.  Place the mouse pointer over the Prefix to be deleted and
    press the left mouse button.  A requester now appears to confirm that
    you really want to delete this prefix.

  . 'Sort Prefixes' gadget sorts the Prefix database.

  . 'Help' gadget activates online help using AmigaGuide.

  . 'Cancel' gadget stops editing the country and cancels only some of the
    changes that were made.

  . 'Okay' gadget stops editing the country and accepts all changes that
    were made.
@EndNode




@Node edit4 "Editing a CallSign Prefix"
All CallSign Prefixes must have a prefix entered.  The suffix is optional
and is only used for a very limited number of countries.  The space is an
illegal character for both the prefix and the suffix and CBLOG will remove
the spaces.

Currently only the CQ zone is used but legal values must be entered for
both the ITU and CQ zones.  CBLOG will inform you of the legal range if
you enter an illegal value.  When a new prefix is added using the 'Add'
gadget, the CQ and ITU zones will be set to the zones for the last CallSign
Prefix in the database for that country.
@EndNode




@Node palette "Screen and Text Colors"
The 'Palette and Text Colors' window allows you to set the colors that you
want for the screen and text.

To edit a Screen Color place the mouse pointer over the color to be changed
in the Color Table and click the left mouse button.  The chosen color will
be displayed to the left of the table.  Use the Red, Green, and Blue slider
gadgets to choose a new color.  The 'Reset' gadget will return the three
sliders to the values that they had before you started to adjust them.

To adjust a Text Color, place the mouse pointer on a name listed in the
Select Pen Color column and click the left mouse button.  For example, to
adjust the color of the title in the 'Contest' window place the mouse
pointer over the word 'Title' that is to the right of the words
'Contest Window:' and press the left mouse button several times until the
color of the word 'Title' cycles to the desired color.

Click the 'Okay' gadget to accept all the changes made or click the
'Cancel' gadget to forget all the changes.
@EndNode




@Node multsymbols "Multiplier Symbols"
Multipliers can be obtained in the CQWW contest for each new country and
each new zone worked for each band.  Special symbols are used to display
these multipliers in the 'Contest' and 'Rate' windows.

The default symbols are the '#' when you have a multiplier both for a new
country and a new zone, the '*' for a new country only multiplier and the
'^' for a new zone only multiplier.

Also in the 'Contest Window' the 'D' is used to indicate that the QSO is
a duplicate QSO for the band.

The multiplier and duplicate symbols can be changed to any letter or number
that you want to use for them.

It is suggested that you decide on which symbols to use before any QSOs are
logged.  To display new symbols with old QSOs, the log will have to be
rescored and resaved to the log file.
@EndNode




@Node printer "Printing the Log"
CBLOG prints all the required reports that must be sent in for the CQ World
Wide Contest.  From the pull-down menus you can select to print each
individual report or to print all the reports.  In the 'Print' window use
the string gadgets to enter your address, country and club name.  The cycle
gadgets are used to set mode and categories.  Use the radio gadget to
select output to the printer or to a disk file.  If you want to print to a
file select the gadget that looks like a disk.  The ASL file requester
that appears can be used to select the path and the file name for the
print file.  Then to print the report press the 'Okay' gadget.
@EndNode




@Node set_radio "Set For Radio or Manual Mode"
The contest can be run in 'Manual Mode' where you change the band in the
'Contest Window' by clicking on its band after you have changed the
frequency on the radio.  To select this mode, click  the 'Use Manual'
gadget.

The other method of changing the band is 'Radio Mode'.  In this mode
the computer monitors the radio and automatically updates the band after
you have changed the frequency on the radio.  Also the computer can control
the radio.  Place the mouse pointer over one of the frequency digits in
the 'Contest Window' and press the left mouse button.  If the pointer is
over the upper half of the digit the value of the digit will decrease by
one but if the pointer is over the lower half of the digit the value of the
digit will increase by one.  The band can be changed by clicking on the
appropriate line in the 'Summary Window'.  The frequency digits will
change and the the radio will be updated.  Control of the radio can be
slow so do not make changes too quickly with the mouse.

In 'Radio Mode' if the computer detects that an illegal frequency has been
set on the radio you will be warned of this.

Select the make of radio you are using by clicking on the cycle gadget.

Note: For Version 1.0 only the Yaesu radio is supported.  If there is
      sufficient demand other radios will be supported.  Also to support
      other radios technical specifications of the radio - computer
      interface will be required.

The radio is connected with an appropriate cable to the connector of either
the standard serial port or a serial port on an optional card installed in
the computer.  The serial port parameters require a device name and unit
number.  For the standard serial port the device name is 'serial.device'
and the unit number is either '0' or '1'.  Check your documentation if
using an optional serial board.  Also set the number of seconds that you
want the computer to wait before checking if you have set a new frequency
on the radio.  After all settings have been made click on the 'Use Radio'
gadget to activate 'Radio Mode'.
@EndNode




@Node radio_frequencies "Set Radio Frequencies"
For each band, there is only a certain range of frequencies that amateur
radio operators can transmit on.  Many radios now automatically block
transmission on illegal frequencies but nevertheless CBLOG also monitors
and does not let you set illegal frequencies.  The minimum and maximum
frequencies for each band can be changed in this window.  The 'Default'
gadget resets all minimums and maximums to the defaults contained in CBLOG.
@EndNode




@Node packet_general "Packet Radio"
Packet radio is controlled through a window which can be switched between
two different sizes.  The 'Switch' and 'Sw' gadgets are used to switch
between these two windows.  The large window is a simple terminal program
window through which you connect and disconnect from the packet radio
station.  The small window displays DXs as they are sent from the packet
radio to you during the contest.

After the serial port is opened the large window will be shown.  If you
have also just turned on or reset your packet radio a copyright message
will be printed to the terminal window.  After the printing is completed
select the 'Connect' gadget and the connect command will be sent to the
packet radio.  The packet radio will respond and print to the terminal that
you are connected to the packet radio station.

The @{" Options " link packet_options} gadget can be used to select various options.

After connection has been made to the packet radio station, any acceptable
command can be sent by typing it into the string gadget labelled 'Command'
and pressing the <return> key.  Currently the data sent by packet radio can
not be captured in a buffer for later viewing.  When you want to disconnect
from packet radio just select the 'Bye' gadget and the command will be sent
to packet.

To have the packet radio send you the list of DXs that it currently has in
its files, you can type 'Show/DX' (without the apostrophes) in the command
string gadget and press the <return> key.  The DXs will be shown in the
terminal window but CBLOG will not remember them.  If you ask for the DXs
by selecting the 'Show/DX' gadget then CBLOG will remember them.

After the list of DXs has been received, switch to the small packet window
using the 'Switch' gadget.  A new list of gadgets is shown.  The 'Sw'
gadget returns to the large terminal window, the @{" Opt " link packet_options} gadget opens a
window so that you can change the options for packet, and the 'Help' gadget
brings up the help file using AmigaGuide.  The remaining four gadgets to
the left are used to scroll through the list of DXs.  The 'T' displays
starting at the top of the list and 'B' gadget displays starting at the
bottom of the list.  The '^' gadget scrolls up through the list one window
full at a time and the 'v' gadget scrolls down through the list one window
full at a time.

DXs disappear from the window as the DX buffer becomes full or time has
elapsed if the @{" timed buffer flush " link packet_options} feature has been activated.  Also DXs
are removed when you log a QSO with that CallSign and band.

If the input buffer for receiving a new CallSign in the 'Contest' window is
empty, you can select a DX from the list.  Place the mouse pointer over the
desired DX in the small packet window and the press the left mouse button.
The CallSign from the DX will be placed in the input buffer in the
'Contest' window just as though you had typed it in and the band will
change to the band of the DX.  If you are also connected to the radio then
the radio will be set to the frequency of the DX.  The DX that you selected
will also be highlighted in the color used for the tile in the 'Contest'
window.
@EndNode




@Node packet_serial "Serial Port Settings for Packet"
The packet radio is connected with an appropriate cable to the
connector of either the standard serial port or a serial port on an
optional card installed in the computer.  The serial port parameters
require a device name and unit number.  For the standard serial port the
device name is 'serial.device' and the unit number is either '0' or '1'.
Check your documentation if using an optional serial board.

Using the cycle gadgets, set Baud, Data Bits, Stop Bits, Parity and
Handshaking according to the specifications in the manual for your packet
radio.  Select 'Okay' gadget to activate the serial port for the the
packet radio or the 'Cancel' gadget to abort.
@EndNode




@Node packet_options "Optional Settings for Packet"
Three gadgets from the main packet window send commands to the packet
radio. These gadgets are 'Connect' for connecting to the packet radio,
'Bye' to log off from packet radio, and 'Show/DX' to instruct packet radio
to send you all DXs currently in its files.  Also the 'Show/DX' gadget
turns on a flag indicating that the DXs should be put into a display list
that will be displayed in the small version of the packet window.  The
characters actually sent to the packet radio when the above gadgets are
selected are determined by the characters entered in the first three
gadgets in the 'Change Packet Options' window.  Change the VE5NN callsign
to that of your packet radio and any other words as required.

The string gadget labelled 'DX Comment' is used for the comment that will
be attached to any DX sent from CBLOG to the packet radio.

When a command is sent to the packet radio it may or may not be echoed
back to CBLOG.  If nothing is printed to the packet window then set the
cycle gadget to 'Echo On' but if the command is printed twice to the packet
window then set the cycle gadget to 'Echo Off'.

When a command is sent to packet radio, a special character must be sent to
terminate the line of characters and inform the packet radio to process the
command.  The termination character is usually a carriage return, 'CR', but
you can also choose a line feed, 'LF', or a carriage return and line feed
combination, 'CR/LF'.  Choose the termination character that your packet
radio requires.

Note: Lines of ASCII characters are terminated with the line feed only for
      Amiga and UNIX computers, with the carriage return only for
      Macintosh computers and with the carriage return/line feed
      combination for MS-DOS, IBM PC and clone computers.

During the contest new DXs will come in and be displayed in the small
packet window.  The new DX will be placed at the head of the list of DXs.
If the 'Immediate Display of New DX' flag is selected (shown by a check-
mark in the gadget) the new DX will be displayed no matter how far down
the list of DXs you may have scrolled.  To disable the immediate display
deselect the gadget (no checkmark shown).  If the 'Flash Screen on New DX'
flag is set the screen will flash to indicate that a new DX has been
received from the packet radio.  If you are operating in either Canada or
the United States, you may not want to know that another DX has been
received from a United States operator.  If so, then set the 'Drop New
United States DX' flag to ignore these DXs.

The buffer that holds DXs is only so big so when it becomes full CBLOG
automatically drops the oldest DX when a new one is received.  During the
contest if you do not try contacting the person in a reasonably short time
period that person will probably be working a different band.  Therefore
you can set how many minutes the DX should be remembered for.  To flush
the DXs as they age set the 'Use' flag.  When the flag is set, CBLOG will
check and flush old DXS about once per minute.
@EndNode




@Node backup "Backing Up the Log File"
During the CQWW Contest there are three ways of backing up the log file.
All three methods are accessed via the pull-down menu.  Backup menu items
will not function unless a log file is open.

Do Backup Now
-------------
Whenever you decide that you want to backup the log file, you select
the 'Do Backup Now' menu item.  An ASL file requester will ask for the
backup file name.  Select a file name and click on the 'OK' gadget and the
backup will be done.  You can backup to either a new or an old file name.
A requester will warn you if an old file is about to be overwritten. Click
on the 'Cancel' gadget if you decide to not do a backup.

This is the poorest method of backup, because you must remember to do it.

Timed Backup
------------
To start timed backup select the 'Timed Backup - Start' menu item.  A
window will open and you can enter the number of minutes that should elapse
between backups.  Click the 'Okay' gadget to start the timed backup.

After the time has elapsed, an ASL file requester will appear.  Click the
'Cancel' gadget if you want to delay the backup until later. Otherwise,
select a new or old file name and click on the 'OK' gadget to do the
backup.  A requester will warn you if an old file is about to be
overwritten.

To stop the timed backup, select the 'Timed Backup - Stop' menu item.  A
requester will ask you to confirm the stop timed backup operation.

The timed backup request can be annoying with the ASL requester opening
on the screen in the middle of a new QSO.

Shadow Backup
-------------
Shadow backup is the best method to use.  Once shadow backup is started
you will not even know that it is happening.

Select the 'Shadow Backup - Start' menu item and an ASL file requester will
appear.  Select the file name for the shadow backup file and click on the
'OK' gadget.  If you already have QSOs in your log, they will be written to
the backup file.  Now whenever a QSO is written to the main log file, it
will also automatically be written to the shadow backup file.

To stop shadow backup select the 'Shadow Backup - Stop' menu item. A 
requester will ask you to confirm the stop request.
@EndNode




@Node zonetype "Select Zone Window Type"
The 'Zone Window' displays 40 CQ zones.  The wide window, normally used
on a HIRES screen, displays 8 zones per row and 5 rows of zones. The narrow
window, normally used on a HIRES INTERLACE screen, displays 4 zones per row
and 10 rows of zones.  Use the cycle gadget to choose the wide or narrow
type of window for display on the current screen.  Once the window type has
been chosen click the 'Okay' gadget.  To abort the operation, click the
'Cancel' gadget.
@EndNode




@Node menus "The Pull-Down Menus"
The pull-down menus are attached to the 'Contest/Console' window.  To be
able to use them the 'Contest' window must be the active window.  This
means that the 'title/drag' bar at the top of the 'Console' window must be
shown in some color that is not the background color of the screen.  If
the 'title' bar is not highlighted place the mouse pointer somewhere over
the 'Console' window and press the left (or select) mouse button.  The
window will now be the active window.

Press and hold down the right (or menu) mouse button.  A title bar will
appear at the top of the screen.  (Note: Some third-party utilities will
open this title bar on the screen at the position the mouse pointer was at
when the right button was pressed.)  Four menus will be shown: @{" Project " link project_menu},
@{" Print " link print_menu}, @{" Windows " link windows_menu}, and @{" Options " link options_menu}.

While still holding down the right mouse button move the mouse pointer to
the top of the screen.  Then move the pointer along the top border.  As the
pointer moves over the menu names a list of items will appear under the
menu names.  Moving the pointer down this list of menu items each item will
become highlighted (change color) as the pointer is moved over it.  Some
menu items have a double arrow to the right of the item name.  This means
that the menu item has sub-items.  To select a menu sub-item move the
pointer right to the sub-item and then downward over the list.  When the
desired menu item or menu sub-item is highlighted then release the right
mouse button and the program will then execute the procedure for that item
or sub-item.  If you decide to not select an item or sub-item then move the
mouse pointer off of all the menus before releasing the right mouse button.

Some menu items or sub-items do not become highlighted when the pointer
passes over them.  The label name is also hard to read.  The menu item is
now called 'ghosted' and the program function related to this menu item
can not be run.  Menu items will keep switching between the ghosted and
non-ghosted states.
@EndNode




@Node project_menu "The Project Menu"
The features of the 'Project' menu' are:

 1. New: This menu item closes any open log files and clears all QSOs from
         memory.

 2. Open Log File -->>New: Opens a new log file.  An ASL file requester
                           allows you to select the path and filename.
   
    Open Log File-->>Old: Open an existing log file via an ASL file
                          requester.

 3. Close Log File: Close any open log files but do not clear QSOs from
                    memory.

 4. Do Backup Now:           see @{" Backing up the log file " link backup}

 5. Timed Backup-->>Start:   see @{" Backing up the log file " link backup}
    Timed Backup-->>Stop:

 6. Shadow Backup-->>Start:  see @{" Backing up the log file " link backup}
    Shadow Backup-->>Stop:

 7. Rescore Log:  If you have edited some QSOs after initially logging them
                  the scoring regarding points and multipliers may not be
                  correct.  To recheck the scoring choose this menu item
                  and everything will be rechecked as though the data was
                  being entered for the first time.  If the score changes
                  resave the data, so that you will not have to do the
                  rescoring again.

 8. Export Delimited: see @{"Export Log As a Delimited File" link export_delimited}. 

 9. About: Displays some brief information about the program.

10. Quit Program:  Choose this menu item when you want to quit the program.
                   A requester will confirm your request to quit.
@EndNode




@Node print_menu "The Print Menu"
The features of the 'Print' menu' are:

1. Summary: Prints the summary page for the report.

2. QSOs: Prints all the QSOs in the order that they were logged.

3. Duplicates: Prints the duplicates for each band.  You can select to
               print any individual band or all the bands.

4. Multipliers: Print the Multipliers report for either Countries or Zones.

5. All Reports: Prints all the above reports.
@EndNode




@Node windows_menu "The Windows Menu"
The features of the 'Windows' menu' are:

 1. Screen Size-->>0 - HiRes:  
    Screen Size-->>1 - HiRes Interlace:
            With WorkBench 2.1 and higher an ASL window opens so that you
            can choose the parameters to be associated with that window.
            The default settings are for HiRes and HiRes Interlace screens.
            You can change them to any type of screen supported by your
            system so the sub-items are also listed as 0 and 1.

 2. Open Screen-->>0 - HiRes:
    Open Screen-->>1 - HiRes Interlace:
            Either of the two Public screens that CBLOG opens can be opened
            by choosing the appropriate menu item.

 3. Close Screen-->>0 - HiRes:
    Close Screen-->>1 - HiRes Interlace:
            Either of the two Public screens that CBLOG opens can be closed
            by choosing the appropriate menu item provided that no windows
            are currently open on the screen.

 4. Change Font-->>Console: Choose the font to be used in the current
                            'Contest/Console' window. An ASL file requester
                            allows you pick a font from those stored on
                            disk.  WorkBench 2.1 and higher also allow the
                            setting of the style of the font.

    Change Font-->>Other: Choose the font to be used in all other windows
                          besides the 'Console' window.  An ASL file
                          requester allows you to pick a font from those
                          stored on disk.  Workbench 2.1 and higher also
                          allow the setting of the style of the font.

    Note: The program was designed with the windows using the Topaz 8 font
          except for the 'Console' window on the HiRes Interlace screen
          which uses the Topaz 14 font. The Topaz 8 font has all characters
          in the font set being 8 pixels high and 8 pixels wide.  The only
          fonts that can be selected are fixed width fonts.  Proportional
          fonts that have varying widths from character to character can
          not be used.  As the size of the font increases the size of the
          windows must also increase proportionately.  When a window can
          not be opened large enough because the size is constrained by the
          screen dimensions, the information in the window will not be
          displayed correctly.  To solve this problem increase the
          dimensions of the screen or pick a smaller font size.

 5. Jump Windows: Windows can be made to move or jump from one Public
                  screen to another Public screen.

 6. Local Time-->>Open: Open a small window to display the local time that
                        the computer is set to.
   
    Local Time-->>Close: Close the window displaying local time.

 7. Packet-->>Open: see @{" Packet Radio " link packet_general}.
   
    Packet-->>Close: Close the window for packet radio.

 8. Zone Window Type: see @{" Select Zone Window Type " link zonetype}.

 9. Summary Window-->>Open:
    Summary Window-->>Close:
             Open and close the 'Summary' window.

10. Partials Window-->>Open:
    Partials Window-->>Close:
             Open and close the 'Partials' window.

11. Rate Window-->>Open:
    Rate Window-->>Close:
             Open and close the 'Rate' window.

12. Zone Window-->>Open:
    Zone Window-->>Close:
             Open and close the 'Zone' window.
@EndNode




@Node options_menu "The Options Menu"
The features of the 'Options' menu' are:

1. User Data-->>Edit: see @{" Setting User Data " link user_data}
   
   User Data-->>Save: An ASL file requester opens so that the path and
                      filename can be selected for saving the user's
                      configuration data to a disk file.  Click on 'Okay'
                      to save the data.

2. CallSign Prefixes-->>Read: An ASL file requester opens so that the path
                              and filename of CallSign Prefixes database
                              file can be entered.  Click on 'Okay' to read
                              the database into RAM memory in the computer.
   
   CallSign Prefixes-->>Save: An ASL file requester opens so that the path
                              and filename can be selected. Click on 'Okay'
                              to save the current CallSign Prefixes data-
                              base in computer memory to the disk file.
                           
   CallSign Prefixes-->>Edit: see @{" Editing Countries and Prefixes " link edit1}
   
   CallSign Prefixes-->>Delete All: Removes all countries and CallSign
                                 prefixes currently in the database in RAM
                                 memory in the computer.

3. Sort-->>Countries: Sorts the country database into alphabetical order.
                      The database MUST be sorted before you start to log
                      QSOs for the contest.
   
   Sort-->>Prefixes: Sorts the CallSign Prefix database into alphabetical
                     order.  The database MUST be sorted before you start
                     to log QSOs for the contest.

4. Calculate Beams: Calculate the beams and then store the CallSign Prefix
                    database.  For speed during the contest these
                    precalculated beams are used for faster display speed.

5. Multiplier Symbols: The menu item activates a window so that you can
                       change the symbols that are used to display the
                       type of multiplier the QSO will be and the symbol
                       that will be used to indicate a duplicate QSO.
                       Change the symbols before you start to log a
                       contest.  If you change the symbols after logging
                       has started, then Rescore and Save the log so that
                       the new symbols will appear throughout the log.

6. Palette: see @{" Screen and Text Colors " link palette}.

7. Set Radio/Manual: see @{" Set For Radio or Manual Mode " link set_radio}.

8. Radio Frequencies: see @{" Set Radio Frequencies " link radio_frequencies}.

9. Timer Reset: When a secondary window opens, the clock showing Zulu time
                will stop updating the time.  This is a normal action as
                temporarily the routines that update the clock can not be
                used.  If the clock does not resume updating after the
                secondary window closes, then use this menu item to restart
                the clock.
@EndNode




@Node export_delimited "Export Log As a Delimited File"
The current QSOs can be exported as a delimited file so that they can then
be imported into LOGic II, Version 2.13, by Personal Database Applications.

The LOGic fields are expected to be in this order:

          1. CALL             9. MODE           17. VIA
          2. QSO_DATE        10. FREQ           18. OPERATOR
          3. TIME_ON         11. BAND           19. CONTEST_ID
          4. TIME_OFF        12. STATE          20. NOTES
          5. RST_SENT        13. COUNTRY        21. ADDRESS
          6. RST_RCVD        14. QSL_SENT       22. PWR
          7. NAME            15. QSL_RCVD
          8. QTH             16. COMMENT

When CBLOG does not have the data required by a field in LOGic it writes a
blank field to the file.  Mode is exported as SSB or CW only.  If you are
operating in Manual Mode (i.e. not reading the radio to get the frequency)
then the frequency exported to LOGic is the minimum of the legal range 
of the band for that QSO plus 0.05 (i.e. if minimum is 1.8 the frequency
exported is 1.85).  Fields 20 and 21 are written as a double tilde (~~)
as per a test file exported from LOGic.

Check your LOGic II manual for instructions on importing a delimited file.
@EndNode
